WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.670 --> 00:00:07.095
Prof: Okay,
we are now at the part of the

00:00:07.095 --> 00:00:10.637
course--
we're coming up to fairly

00:00:10.637 --> 00:00:14.350
modern times,
it's been a very breathless run

00:00:14.350 --> 00:00:18.248
from six million years of
chimpanzee evolution through

00:00:18.248 --> 00:00:20.777
many--
few million years of human

00:00:20.777 --> 00:00:24.282
evolution,
and we're coming up to more or

00:00:24.282 --> 00:00:28.388
less the 1960s,
which is the period of the

00:00:28.388 --> 00:00:34.810
greatest percentage increase in
human population on earth ever.

00:00:34.810 --> 00:00:39.215
So this is the peak of what's
called the population explosion

00:00:39.215 --> 00:00:43.621
and we're going to be talking
about that until almost the end

00:00:43.621 --> 00:00:45.090
of the term now.
 

00:00:45.090 --> 00:00:52.743
I have to tell you a little
bit, truth in teaching or

00:00:52.743 --> 00:00:54.510
something.
 

00:00:54.510 --> 00:00:59.540
How I got interested in this
topic.

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:02.289
When I was just a little bit
older then you are now,

00:01:02.289 --> 00:01:07.209
I did the fairly usual thing of
going--

00:01:07.209 --> 00:01:10.299
putting on my short pants and
going around the world,

00:01:10.299 --> 00:01:15.007
around Asia anyway,
with almost no money in my

00:01:15.007 --> 00:01:15.950
pocket.
 

00:01:15.950 --> 00:01:18.805
You all, if you have never done
that, you should do it

00:01:18.805 --> 00:01:21.879
definitely, and after you
graduate college is a great time

00:01:21.879 --> 00:01:22.580
to do it.
 

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:25.730
One of the places I went to was
Hong Kong.

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:28.933
Now Hong Kong at that time
there were huge numbers of

00:01:28.933 --> 00:01:30.720
people coming out of China.
 

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:34.050
China was still extraordinarily
poor at the time,

00:01:34.050 --> 00:01:36.709
and any time anybody could
leave they left,

00:01:36.709 --> 00:01:41.069
and so Hong Kong was incredibly
crowded with very poor people

00:01:41.069 --> 00:01:45.140
and it's still an incredibly
crowded place of course,

00:01:45.140 --> 00:01:49.190
and migrants are still coming
out if they can.

00:01:49.190 --> 00:01:53.760
One of the--where were these
people going to live?

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:56.060
There were hillsides with
shanty towns,

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:59.190
lots and lots of shanty towns,
but also the--

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:02.170
it's right on the ocean,
it's an island,

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:05.241
part of it's an island,
so the water is free so many

00:02:05.241 --> 00:02:07.650
people were living in little
sampans,

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:13.250
little boats called sampans
in--just in the harbor docked

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:15.848
sort of almost anywhere.
 

00:02:15.848 --> 00:02:19.066
I thought well that's
interesting, and one of my

00:02:19.066 --> 00:02:22.966
friends, I had a number of
Chinese friends took me to look

00:02:22.966 --> 00:02:24.128
at the boats.
 

00:02:24.128 --> 00:02:27.806
It was interesting,
I wasn't yet really interested

00:02:27.806 --> 00:02:32.311
in demography but I couldn't
help notice that basically every

00:02:32.311 --> 00:02:36.138
boat had a little girl on it
11,12, 13 or something,

00:02:36.138 --> 00:02:37.639
maybe younger.
 

00:02:37.639 --> 00:02:40.910
And then we got invited on the
boat,

00:02:40.910 --> 00:02:44.774
one of the first--one of the
boats and people were extremely

00:02:44.774 --> 00:02:46.739
polite,
even the very poor,

00:02:46.739 --> 00:02:51.080
very polite and a lot of bowing
and shaking hands on my part,

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:52.930
and they wanted to offer me
something,

00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:55.400
a little bit of tea,
a little bit of rice cake,

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:58.538
they're just as wonderful as
they could be.

00:02:58.538 --> 00:03:01.270
I noticed that when something
had to be done like the tea had

00:03:01.270 --> 00:03:03.443
to be gotten,
or this that or the other

00:03:03.443 --> 00:03:06.908
thing, it was that little girl
that was doing all the work.

00:03:06.908 --> 00:03:09.562
Okay, so what,
that's one the kids,

00:03:09.562 --> 00:03:12.758
it's good for kids to have some
chores.

00:03:12.758 --> 00:03:15.699
Then since--they didn't have
didn't have television or a lot

00:03:15.699 --> 00:03:18.688
of entertainment and here was
this Westerner and they weren't

00:03:18.688 --> 00:03:21.580
so used to seeing a lot of
Westerners on their boats--

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:23.669
I sort of got passed from boat
to boat.

00:03:23.669 --> 00:03:25.280
When you go walking around the
world that's a very good,

00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:28.528
if you go to places where they
don't see Westerners you can get

00:03:28.528 --> 00:03:32.072
passed on very easily--
so in boat after boat--and this

00:03:32.072 --> 00:03:35.979
phenomenon repeated itself,
that there was this little girl

00:03:35.979 --> 00:03:39.210
in every boat and she seemed to
be doing all the work.

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:44.038
Finally, I asked my friends,
what's going on here?

00:03:44.038 --> 00:03:47.590
A little hard to get the
information out of them,

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:52.950
but in actual fact it was a
form of shall we say family

00:03:52.950 --> 00:03:57.291
population control that the--
there--this was a

00:03:57.291 --> 00:04:01.743
non-contracepting population so
children just coming and they

00:04:01.743 --> 00:04:06.271
couldn't support the number of
children that they had and they

00:04:06.271 --> 00:04:08.870
did not value girls very much.
 

00:04:08.870 --> 00:04:12.646
What they did is,
basically, they sold the girls

00:04:12.646 --> 00:04:17.209
from one boat to the next boat,
and then the little girls were

00:04:17.209 --> 00:04:19.524
basically servants,
again you can use the word

00:04:19.524 --> 00:04:23.005
slave it you want,
but servants in whatever boat

00:04:23.005 --> 00:04:27.250
they had been sold to,
and some money changed hands,

00:04:27.250 --> 00:04:31.502
of course all illegal because
Hong Kong was then under British

00:04:31.502 --> 00:04:32.129
rules.
 

00:04:32.129 --> 00:04:35.639
It's illegal almost everywhere
anyway.

00:04:35.639 --> 00:04:40.065
They were just working,
doing as much work as could be

00:04:40.065 --> 00:04:41.819
gotten out of them.
 

00:04:41.819 --> 00:04:44.916
Well that was very sad,
but it wasn't a disaster

00:04:44.916 --> 00:04:47.750
because everybody was living
very poorly.

00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:52.779
Then later, same trip,
with my medical connections,

00:04:52.779 --> 00:04:55.870
I got to tour one of the big
British--

00:04:55.870 --> 00:04:58.762
Queen Elizabeth Hospital,
one of these big city

00:04:58.762 --> 00:05:01.095
hospitals,
it had ward after ward,

00:05:01.095 --> 00:05:03.930
and one of the things I was
taken to see--

00:05:03.930 --> 00:05:06.889
tuberculosis was a very big
problem back then,

00:05:06.889 --> 00:05:10.379
leprosy was a problem,
tuberculosis was a problem.

00:05:10.379 --> 00:05:12.120
I did something stupid with
leprosy I visited--

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:16.459
there was a leper colony on an
island off of Hong Kong and they

00:05:16.459 --> 00:05:20.245
were constructing stuff,
and I cannot stand around while

00:05:20.245 --> 00:05:23.490
people are working and me not so
I grabbed a pitch--

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:29.329
a pickax and started working
with them and of course the

00:05:29.329 --> 00:05:31.240
pickax is rough.
 

00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:34.677
It's made of not terribly well
polished wood and there I was

00:05:34.677 --> 00:05:37.300
banging away with it and it rubs
whatever--

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:41.343
Leprosy is a bacteria that gets
into your skin and the only way

00:05:41.343 --> 00:05:44.670
to get it is to get that leprosy
into your skin,

00:05:44.670 --> 00:05:48.137
so the lepers had been working
with it and rubbing it into

00:05:48.137 --> 00:05:52.029
their skin and they were rubbing
into the wood of the ax and then

00:05:52.029 --> 00:05:52.759
onto me.
 

00:05:52.759 --> 00:05:57.254
I did not get--it was really
stupid in retrospect but you do

00:05:57.254 --> 00:06:01.370
a lot of stupid things and I did
not catch leprosy,

00:06:01.370 --> 00:06:05.244
and in fact,
by that time most--they had a

00:06:05.244 --> 00:06:07.963
drug,
an antibiotic against leprosy

00:06:07.963 --> 00:06:12.028
and most of the leprosy bacillus
in these people was dead,

00:06:12.028 --> 00:06:15.550
so it probably wasn't quite as
dangerous as it might have been.

00:06:15.550 --> 00:06:20.723
Anyway, I did not catch leprosy;
you can check my hand and so

00:06:20.723 --> 00:06:21.389
forth.
 

00:06:21.389 --> 00:06:24.678
The people there had the
old--this is an aside but it's

00:06:24.678 --> 00:06:26.689
about poverty so I'll tell you.
 

00:06:26.689 --> 00:06:30.399
Leprosy affects the nerve cells
and it doesn't make--

00:06:30.399 --> 00:06:32.860
directly make your fingers or
nose fall off,

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:36.009
but you don't feel wounds,
so you don't--

00:06:36.009 --> 00:06:36.910
because you don't have the
nerve cells--

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:41.853
so you don't take care of
wounds, eventually the fingers

00:06:41.853 --> 00:06:45.978
get infected and damaged,
the damage is kind of constant

00:06:45.978 --> 00:06:47.910
and parts of you fall off
actually.

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:49.750
But it's not the leprosy
bacteria itself,

00:06:49.750 --> 00:06:52.463
which only attacks nerves,
it's the damage that you're not

00:06:52.463 --> 00:06:54.480
paying--
you're not noticing,

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.100
you're not aware of.
 

00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:58.430
Sorry that was an excursion.
 

00:06:58.430 --> 00:07:01.040
Leprosy was a big thing in Hong
Kong at that time,

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:05.403
as was tuberculosis and in the
big British hospital I went in

00:07:05.403 --> 00:07:08.750
and one of the things I saw was
huge wards,

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:14.187
they're big places with--again
I saw a ward full of these just

00:07:14.187 --> 00:07:19.089
pubescent or pre-pubescent girls
and they all had TB.

00:07:19.089 --> 00:07:22.380
Then there was two or three of
these wards actually,

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:26.317
so a very large number of girls
there, and I said what's going

00:07:26.317 --> 00:07:26.769
on?
 

00:07:26.769 --> 00:07:29.639
Then the full story came out.
 

00:07:29.639 --> 00:07:32.874
That yes, indeed,
there is a lot of selling of

00:07:32.874 --> 00:07:36.269
the children between boats,
and yes they work,

00:07:36.269 --> 00:07:39.853
and because they're underfed
and overworked and TB is

00:07:39.853 --> 00:07:44.209
rampant,
these girls get tuberculosis.

00:07:44.209 --> 00:07:48.249
Then what happens is they take
them to the health station and

00:07:48.249 --> 00:07:52.355
the doctors say you've got to
build up this girl and they give

00:07:52.355 --> 00:07:53.769
them milk powder.
 

00:07:53.769 --> 00:07:58.160
Milk powder is taken,
and what do you think they do

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:00.180
with the milk powder?
 

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:03.879
Give it to the boy child,
so the girl gets sicker,

00:08:03.879 --> 00:08:06.860
and then she's getting quite
sick and she's brought back,

00:08:06.860 --> 00:08:10.170
and now she's given medicine,
an antibiotic,

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:11.980
and guess what happens with
medicine?

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:16.636
Taken to the market,
sold, the money is used to buy

00:08:16.636 --> 00:08:19.990
rice or milk for the boy
children.

00:08:19.990 --> 00:08:22.800
Eventually--so TB,
as you're probably aware,

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:25.752
gets the lungs,
it can also get in the long

00:08:25.752 --> 00:08:28.593
bones of the body,
and eventually it infects the

00:08:28.593 --> 00:08:30.379
long bones and the long bones
start--

00:08:30.379 --> 00:08:33.363
huge amounts of pus builds up
and eventually it breaks through

00:08:33.363 --> 00:08:37.020
the skin,
so someone who has a child with

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:42.668
this kind of long bone
tuberculosis sees basically pus,

00:08:42.668 --> 00:08:45.658
the skin eventually breaks and
the pus starts pouring out,

00:08:45.658 --> 00:08:49.643
and the parents are terribly
afraid and they're afraid for

00:08:49.643 --> 00:08:52.731
their biological kids,
their biological sons

00:08:52.731 --> 00:08:53.500
especially.
 

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:59.520
As soon as this happens to the
girl they just dump her at the

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:05.140
British--at whatever the public
hospital is and they just

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:07.450
abandon them there.
 

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:12.357
What the doctors told me was
that the girls are now 13 or 14,

00:09:12.357 --> 00:09:17.267
the tuberculosis is so far gone
that there's nothing they can

00:09:17.267 --> 00:09:17.840
do.
 

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:20.788
And the girls die.
 

00:09:20.788 --> 00:09:25.914
This was my first introduction
to that nexus of extreme

00:09:25.914 --> 00:09:29.770
poverty,
extremely crowded conditions,

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:33.154
overpopulation,
and I'm not saying the causal

00:09:33.154 --> 00:09:36.803
relationship between those two
is a complicated story which we

00:09:36.803 --> 00:09:39.466
will get to,
but that nexus of--you always

00:09:39.466 --> 00:09:43.235
see, whenever you see incredibly
dense populations you always see

00:09:43.235 --> 00:09:46.474
this kind of poverty and the
kinds of things that people

00:09:46.474 --> 00:09:47.240
undergo.
 

00:09:47.240 --> 00:09:50.440
I was trying to put myself in
the mind of a parent,

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:54.408
what kind of a situation are
they are in,

00:09:54.408 --> 00:09:59.000
that they sell their daughters
to fairly certain death and the

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.009
situation is as I've described
to you.

00:10:02.009 --> 00:10:07.183
Even though I saw this as a
huge--as a very large phenomenon

00:10:07.183 --> 00:10:10.778
I've never seen this in any
literature.

00:10:10.778 --> 00:10:12.418
I've never seen an academic
paper about it,

00:10:12.418 --> 00:10:15.970
I've never seen a newspaper
story about it,

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:18.490
it's not discussed in
demographic circles,

00:10:18.490 --> 00:10:21.179
and some public health circles
which I'm aware,

00:10:21.179 --> 00:10:24.769
it just isn't brought up.
 

00:10:24.769 --> 00:10:27.604
I'm thinking to myself,
I was not a scholar of this

00:10:27.604 --> 00:10:30.099
thing, and I said,
"have I misremembered

00:10:30.099 --> 00:10:30.950
this?"
 

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:33.774
You very frequently misremember
things, have I blown up,

00:10:33.774 --> 00:10:37.009
did I see one or two cases and
have I somehow aggrandized it.

00:10:37.009 --> 00:10:39.046
I eventually,
after telling the story quite a

00:10:39.046 --> 00:10:41.676
bit,
even in the early runnings of

00:10:41.676 --> 00:10:44.586
this class,
I started doubting that

00:10:44.586 --> 00:10:47.394
this--that somehow--
why such a big thing,

00:10:47.394 --> 00:10:48.490
why wasn't it shown?
 

00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:50.330
One year I decided:
this is the last year;

00:10:50.330 --> 00:10:52.947
I'm not going to tell this
story again because I don't have

00:10:52.947 --> 00:10:54.029
any references for it.
 

00:10:54.029 --> 00:10:57.227
Everything I say I try to--if a
student comes to me I can give

00:10:57.227 --> 00:11:00.322
you a reference and you can see
in the notes a lot of things

00:11:00.322 --> 00:11:03.573
have little references which you
probably can't read but if you

00:11:03.573 --> 00:11:06.615
call me or email me I'll tell
you what that little scribble

00:11:06.615 --> 00:11:07.350
means.
 

00:11:07.350 --> 00:11:11.470
Anyway at the end of that
lecture, actually it was about

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.767
two lectures later,
because there was an exam

00:11:14.767 --> 00:11:17.090
coming up right after that.
 

00:11:17.090 --> 00:11:20.139
More than in this class,
in previous years,

00:11:20.139 --> 00:11:23.288
students used to come up and we
used to spend a half an hour or

00:11:23.288 --> 00:11:25.879
an hour discussing whatever they
want to discuss.

00:11:25.879 --> 00:11:29.293
And one girl stayed by the side
and then when everybody is gone

00:11:29.293 --> 00:11:31.820
she came up to me,
a little bit shy,

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:35.850
and said, "Thank you for
telling that story.

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:38.629
My mother was one of those
girls."

00:11:38.629 --> 00:11:41.096
What she knew,
from her mother,

00:11:41.096 --> 00:11:46.198
was basically what I had said,
but the difference was that

00:11:46.198 --> 00:11:50.980
this was her biological mother,
and this wasn't an abandoned

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:51.379
girl.
 

00:11:51.379 --> 00:11:54.190
She said she remembered being
in the hospital with all girls

00:11:54.190 --> 00:11:59.277
basically--
the mother--I said "Oh my

00:11:59.277 --> 00:12:02.403
gosh,
would your mother come to class

00:12:02.403 --> 00:12:05.700
and describe what this situation
was like?"

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:09.461
Yes, the mother was in fact a
professor at a college in New

00:12:09.461 --> 00:12:11.096
Jersey,
not Princeton,

00:12:11.096 --> 00:12:13.918
and she came up here and
described it,

00:12:13.918 --> 00:12:18.716
and again, described it in
great detail and more or less as

00:12:18.716 --> 00:12:20.370
I've described it.
 

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:23.139
She said that when she was in
the hospital,

00:12:23.139 --> 00:12:24.379
she saw all the other little
girls,

00:12:24.379 --> 00:12:27.149
more or less the same age,
same medical problem,

00:12:27.149 --> 00:12:28.841
and she said,
as a little girl she always

00:12:28.841 --> 00:12:31.101
wondered why their parent--
their mother didn't come to

00:12:31.101 --> 00:12:32.687
visit them,
why their parents didn't come

00:12:32.687 --> 00:12:33.250
to visit them.
 

00:12:33.250 --> 00:12:36.682
She was one of the few whose
mother--I guess the father,

00:12:36.682 --> 00:12:40.240
I don't really remember that
detail, did come to visit.

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:44.784
Well the doctors kind of
noticed that this girl had a

00:12:44.784 --> 00:12:50.029
bio-parent and so they took her
out of the big ward and put a

00:12:50.029 --> 00:12:54.750
lot of incredibly special effort
into this one girl and

00:12:54.750 --> 00:13:00.168
eventually she got the bacteria
out of her and survived.

00:13:00.168 --> 00:13:06.201
She was--walked like this,
missing a hip and had a fair

00:13:06.201 --> 00:13:10.558
number of sequelae from the bone
TB,

00:13:10.558 --> 00:13:13.831
but she got cured,
grew up, managed to get

00:13:13.831 --> 00:13:16.067
educated,
migrate to America,

00:13:16.067 --> 00:13:19.851
and became a professor at,
as I say at a college in New

00:13:19.851 --> 00:13:23.519
Jersey and had a daughter at
Yale taking this course.

00:13:23.519 --> 00:13:30.967
It's one of the miracle stories
but I'm convinced now that I

00:13:30.967 --> 00:13:34.629
didn't dream this stuff up.
 

00:13:34.629 --> 00:13:38.404
That's really my personal
motivation, that started of

00:13:38.404 --> 00:13:42.253
course the motivation for
being--doing all this course

00:13:42.253 --> 00:13:42.980
stuff.
 

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:51.100
What's the word we describe for
this era of the 1960s?

00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:54.870
The population explosion.
 

00:13:54.870 --> 00:13:57.019
Why do we use the word
explosion?

00:13:57.019 --> 00:14:01.899
It's a rather emotive kind of
word and it's for this reason,

00:14:01.899 --> 00:14:06.788
that here is a somewhat
fanciful recreation of history,

00:14:06.788 --> 00:14:09.511
but we know it can't be very
much different from this because

00:14:09.511 --> 00:14:11.618
we know what the--
