and a lot of what we consume is
frivolous like Hummers and great

00:29:12.519 --> 00:29:15.182
big--
some little person driving this

00:29:15.182 --> 00:29:19.472
great big SUV that they never
carry anything heavy and they

00:29:19.472 --> 00:29:23.911
certainly don't have to drive
over logs or something which an

00:29:23.911 --> 00:29:26.130
SUV is actually good for.
 

00:29:26.130 --> 00:29:30.390
The over consumption depletes
the world's resources,

00:29:30.390 --> 00:29:33.818
increases pollution,
destruction of habitat,

00:29:33.818 --> 00:29:37.833
etcetera, etcetera,
etcetera, so environmental

00:29:37.833 --> 00:29:43.720
misery is largely caused by rich
people consuming profligately,

00:29:43.720 --> 00:29:47.538
unnecessarily and profligately.
 

00:29:47.538 --> 00:29:51.380
The other side of the coin is
poverty,

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:55.747
the world is definitely split
and the split is getting wider

00:29:55.747 --> 00:29:59.536
between poverty and over--
people who over consume - and

00:29:59.536 --> 00:30:03.323
their problem of course is under
consumption and they lead to all

00:30:03.323 --> 00:30:06.932
of the problems of poverty which
I have discussed in Hong Kong

00:30:06.932 --> 00:30:10.009
and I don't have to tell you
very much about what the

00:30:10.009 --> 00:30:12.848
problems in the world of poor
people are.

00:30:12.848 --> 00:30:14.400
We have these two opposite
problems,

00:30:14.400 --> 00:30:18.318
what I call environmental
misery and human misery,

00:30:18.318 --> 00:30:22.575
and they're both very largely
the result of too rapid

00:30:22.575 --> 00:30:26.851
population growth that we might,
in some utopian scenario,

00:30:26.851 --> 00:30:28.769
eventually be able to cope
with,

00:30:28.769 --> 00:30:32.980
say the population levels that
we have now, maybe.

00:30:32.980 --> 00:30:35.590
But, at the rate of growth it's
obvious just looking around you

00:30:35.590 --> 00:30:37.594
that our technology,
our economy,

00:30:37.594 --> 00:30:41.645
our governments,
have not been able to cope with

00:30:41.645 --> 00:30:42.940
this so far.
 

00:30:42.940 --> 00:30:45.816
It's very interesting as a
political note that there are

00:30:45.816 --> 00:30:48.170
these two faces of the
population problem,

00:30:48.170 --> 00:30:51.868
the environmental problem and
the people misery problem,

00:30:51.868 --> 00:30:55.279
and it's amazing how people
focus on one or the other.

00:30:55.279 --> 00:30:59.026
There's people like--work in
planned parenthood and various

00:30:59.026 --> 00:31:01.286
feminists and women's
organizations,

00:31:01.286 --> 00:31:03.868
they're interested in people
misery.

00:31:03.868 --> 00:31:06.548
They always talk about poverty
and its attendant problems.

00:31:06.548 --> 00:31:08.292
Then there's the
environmentalists and they're

00:31:08.292 --> 00:31:10.269
worried about trees and the
survival of animals,

00:31:10.269 --> 00:31:13.269
and forests,
and nature and both are of

00:31:13.269 --> 00:31:17.769
course very important and very
good causes to work on,

00:31:17.769 --> 00:31:20.258
but it is absolutely mind
boggling how rarely you find

00:31:20.258 --> 00:31:23.132
anybody that's sort of,
is really in any way,

00:31:23.132 --> 00:31:28.029
concerned about both problems,
or in any way realizes how

00:31:28.029 --> 00:31:33.250
population is the centerpiece of
both of these problems.

00:31:33.250 --> 00:31:38.596
Let me talk just a little bit
about over consumption and who's

00:31:38.596 --> 00:31:42.539
the number one bad guy in over
consumption?

00:31:42.539 --> 00:31:44.900
We are.
 

00:31:44.900 --> 00:31:49.009
So here's the story for--some
of the story for the United

00:31:49.009 --> 00:31:49.670
States.
 

00:31:49.670 --> 00:31:57.119
This is the growth of the
United States population from

00:31:57.119 --> 00:31:59.190
1900 to 2000.
 

00:31:59.190 --> 00:32:06.759
We in 1900 had about 75 million
and in 2006 this--

00:32:06.759 --> 00:32:13.798
so in 2006 we passed 300
million people and that's a

00:32:13.798 --> 00:32:21.663
quadrupling that our population
has quadrupled in that one

00:32:21.663 --> 00:32:23.318
century.
 

00:32:23.318 --> 00:32:27.064
We were almost like an
underdeveloped country in our

00:32:27.064 --> 00:32:28.900
population growth rate.
 

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:31.460
That is up to the--almost
current,

00:32:31.460 --> 00:32:35.410
and here is again the latest
Census Bureau thing from--

00:32:35.410 --> 00:32:38.805
again this was--just got it out
of the computer last night

00:32:38.805 --> 00:32:40.898
actually,
the latest numbers,

00:32:40.898 --> 00:32:44.672
that here's the standard--
one of the standard things is

00:32:44.672 --> 00:32:49.785
give you 100 year time frame,
currently they're using 1950 to

00:32:49.785 --> 00:32:52.507
2050 and we are,
as you know,

00:32:52.507 --> 00:32:55.137
right about here and here is
the U.S.

00:32:55.137 --> 00:32:59.377
population growth rate and just
almost a perfectly straight

00:32:59.377 --> 00:33:00.108
line.
 

00:33:00.108 --> 00:33:03.563
There is no prediction that the
U.S.

00:33:03.563 --> 00:33:08.990
is going to slow down in its
population growth rate,

00:33:08.990 --> 00:33:12.318
we are growing at about three
million a year,

00:33:12.318 --> 00:33:17.871
currently that's 1% of a year,
and because of natural increase

00:33:17.871 --> 00:33:23.150
that's births over deaths of
people already in America,

00:33:23.150 --> 00:33:29.130
plus immigration,
we're just going here.

00:33:29.130 --> 00:33:34.672
In our population growth rate,
it's about 2/3 births over

00:33:34.672 --> 00:33:40.608
deaths of citizens already here
and about 1/3 immigration.

00:33:40.608 --> 00:33:45.233
Of immigration,
the guesses are that it's about

00:33:45.233 --> 00:33:49.843
2/3 legal and 1/3 illegal,
obviously the illegal is an

00:33:49.843 --> 00:33:51.868
enormous guess,
the absolute number,

00:33:51.868 --> 00:33:53.788
the percentage of anything that
it is,

00:33:53.788 --> 00:33:56.809
if you look at how they come up
with these numbers it's really

00:33:56.809 --> 00:33:57.900
'seat-of-the-pants.'
 

00:33:57.900 --> 00:34:03.423
We don't know very much about
the magnitude of illegal

00:34:03.423 --> 00:34:08.739
immigration but it's an enormous
political issue.

00:34:08.739 --> 00:34:13.780
Now on the consumption side,
of course we consume so much,

00:34:13.780 --> 00:34:19.443
and again numbers vary kind of
wildly but the range of numbers

00:34:19.443 --> 00:34:24.644
are that an American consumes
something between 20 and 40

00:34:24.644 --> 00:34:30.309
times what a person in a
developing country will consume.

00:34:30.309 --> 00:34:34.219
If you multiplied our three
million population growth a year

00:34:34.219 --> 00:34:37.599
by a consumption factor of 20
that's equivalent--

00:34:37.599 --> 00:34:41.900
a population growth of 60
million poor people and so if

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:46.998
you do it that way it looks like
that our population growth is as

00:34:46.998 --> 00:34:51.617
damaging to the resource and
environmental situation of the

00:34:51.617 --> 00:34:55.840
world as the whole rest of world
put together,

00:34:55.840 --> 00:34:59.996
and that's just considering our
population increase not the

00:34:59.996 --> 00:35:04.369
population base which is also
consuming at this great rate.

00:35:04.369 --> 00:35:10.170
We are--indeed it is certainly
correct that we are a tremendous

00:35:10.170 --> 00:35:15.409
strain on the environment and
resources of the earth,

00:35:15.409 --> 00:35:17.159
and as I showed you it's not
getting better,

00:35:17.159 --> 00:35:21.010
our population is just
increasing.

00:35:21.010 --> 00:35:23.481
You have to balance against
that that a lot of our

00:35:23.481 --> 00:35:26.356
population growth is of course
people coming in from other

00:35:26.356 --> 00:35:28.844
countries so that it's not,
in some sense,

00:35:28.844 --> 00:35:32.030
Americans who are getting
richer but its poor people

00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:34.030
coming in and getting richer.
 

00:35:34.030 --> 00:35:38.445
You can play these numbers in
all different ways and we'll

00:35:38.445 --> 00:35:41.389
talk about the politics in a
moment.

00:35:41.389 --> 00:35:46.518
The U.S. Census Bureau used
to say that we will reach--that

00:35:46.518 --> 00:35:47.226
the U.S.
 

00:35:47.226 --> 00:35:52.179
population will reach 300
million by the year 2050.

00:35:52.179 --> 00:35:56.500
We reached that number 44 years
earlier than the Census Bureau

00:35:56.500 --> 00:35:58.644
thought,
and we are still growing and

00:35:58.644 --> 00:36:01.668
now the Census Bureau says there
is no sign of stabilization at

00:36:01.668 --> 00:36:02.010
all.
 

00:36:02.010 --> 00:36:05.815
They cannot give you a number
at which they think the U.S.

00:36:05.815 --> 00:36:09.485
population will stabilize,
because as far out as anybody

00:36:09.485 --> 00:36:13.625
can project, there's no reason
to believe that stabilization is

00:36:13.625 --> 00:36:14.559
in view.
 

00:36:14.559 --> 00:36:23.730
Now some of the argumentation
is that again people--

00:36:23.730 --> 00:36:28.018
this is a very political issue
and half the people say,

00:36:28.018 --> 00:36:29.820
'it's all those poor people
that are over reproducing,

00:36:29.820 --> 00:36:32.518
can't they learn some self
control?'

00:36:32.518 --> 00:36:34.914
Then you have people saying,
'all those Americans and

00:36:34.914 --> 00:36:37.541
Japanese that consume like
crazy, can't they use some self

00:36:37.541 --> 00:36:38.139
control?'
 

00:36:38.139 --> 00:36:42.664
It's an extremely sterile
argument that goes on and on and

00:36:42.664 --> 00:36:47.188
people don't think beyond two or
three sentences into that

00:36:47.188 --> 00:36:48.219
argument.
 

00:36:48.219 --> 00:36:52.688
As I'll tell you,
if you do it out numerically

00:36:52.688 --> 00:36:58.842
the increasing damage is more or
less equal and it depends more

00:36:58.842 --> 00:37:04.900
critically as Americans usually
blame ourselves that we're the

00:37:04.900 --> 00:37:08.581
problem,
there's a very kind of--I don't

00:37:08.581 --> 00:37:12.681
want to use the word racist but
a very Euro-Americo centric

00:37:12.681 --> 00:37:16.429
argument because the presumption
is when it says,

00:37:16.429 --> 00:37:19.920
well we're the consumers
and--all the poor people,

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:22.699
we don't have to worry about,
is that they will stay poor.

00:37:22.699 --> 00:37:25.876
It's a Western assumption that
poor people are going to stay

00:37:25.876 --> 00:37:28.333
poor and they're not--
not only are they not consumers

00:37:28.333 --> 00:37:30.277
now,
but they're never going to be

00:37:30.277 --> 00:37:30.929
consumers.
 

00:37:30.929 --> 00:37:33.030
And that is just nonsense.
 

00:37:33.030 --> 00:37:35.690
We've seen how the Chinese have
come up enormously,

00:37:35.690 --> 00:37:37.820
the Indians have come up
enormously,

00:37:37.820 --> 00:37:40.369
the Indonesians have come up
enormously,

00:37:40.369 --> 00:37:44.387
everywhere in the world these
vast numbers of poor people are

00:37:44.387 --> 00:37:47.000
now starting to be serious
consumers.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:51.213
I think the CO_2
production in China I think has

00:37:51.213 --> 00:37:56.757
just outpaced the United States,
but I didn't look that up

00:37:56.757 --> 00:37:59.632
recently,
and so there are equal

00:37:59.632 --> 00:38:03.925
problems, so if one gets out of
one's head the idea that poor

00:38:03.925 --> 00:38:06.929
people are going to stay poor
forever,

00:38:06.929 --> 00:38:11.072
which is a pre-globalization
idea--now a worker in China can

00:38:11.072 --> 00:38:15.494
compete with a worker in America
and eventually there's going to

00:38:15.494 --> 00:38:16.969
be some leveling.
 

00:38:16.969 --> 00:38:20.184
I think the proper thing is,
if you think there are too many

00:38:20.184 --> 00:38:22.829
people on earth,
for either human misery issues

00:38:22.829 --> 00:38:25.030
or environmental misery issues
or both,

00:38:25.030 --> 00:38:28.030
any birth you should consider
more or less equal.

00:38:28.030 --> 00:38:31.280
Preventing a birth in America,
in Japan,

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:34.556
and Indonesia,
everywhere that in the not too

00:38:34.556 --> 00:38:39.101
distant future these people are
going to be more or less equal

00:38:39.101 --> 00:38:43.570
and we'll see in next lecture
what the people themselves want

00:38:43.570 --> 00:38:46.030
with respect to this thing.
 

00:38:46.030 --> 00:38:51.590
I hope after this course that
none of you get involved in the

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:56.503
sterile argument of us versus
them, it doesn't get you

00:38:56.503 --> 00:38:57.710
anywhere.
 

00:38:57.710 --> 00:39:03.045
In the world as it is today
most of the--almost all of the

00:39:03.045 --> 00:39:07.539
population growth is in the
poorest countries.

00:39:07.539 --> 00:39:11.614
Again statistics are pretty
bad, there's something like 95%

00:39:11.614 --> 00:39:15.126
of population growth in the
world is in the poorest

00:39:15.126 --> 00:39:16.110
countries.
 

00:39:16.110 --> 00:39:18.849
As you know,
new people need schools,

00:39:18.849 --> 00:39:20.900
they need healthcare,
they need a place to live,

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:24.170
they need jobs and all of this
takes money,

00:39:24.170 --> 00:39:26.456
takes capital,
and that's what the poor

00:39:26.456 --> 00:39:29.585
countries are missing,
they don't have the capital,

00:39:29.585 --> 00:39:32.719
they usually don't have the
technological expertise,

00:39:32.719 --> 00:39:36.409
they don't have often the
quality of government that can

00:39:36.409 --> 00:39:40.166
cope with these enormous
problems so it's the places that

00:39:40.166 --> 00:39:44.327
are least capable of coping with
a population increase that are

00:39:44.327 --> 00:39:46.340
in fact saddled with it.
 

00:39:46.340 --> 00:39:52.489
The magnitude of this growth is
incredible.

00:39:52.489 --> 00:39:57.610
As far out as we can project
the poor countries are going to

00:39:57.610 --> 00:40:01.949
have to build a city equivalent
of one million--

00:40:01.949 --> 00:40:07.715
a city to cope with a million
people every week for the next

00:40:07.715 --> 00:40:11.920
45 years which is as far as we
projected.

00:40:11.920 --> 00:40:14.630
If you look at--you know the
big cities Shanghai,

00:40:14.630 --> 00:40:18.681
Beijing and China,
just pick almost any name and

00:40:18.681 --> 00:40:23.768
go to an almanac and you'll see
there's so many mega million

00:40:23.768 --> 00:40:27.132
cities in China that--
cities even that I've never

00:40:27.132 --> 00:40:28.804
heard of,
when you look up their

00:40:28.804 --> 00:40:31.842
population, they're in the
millions and a place like New

00:40:31.842 --> 00:40:34.329
York with seven million people
is nothing.

00:40:34.329 --> 00:40:38.708
Sweden, where I lived in Sweden
for a while, has like seven to

00:40:38.708 --> 00:40:40.360
eight million people.
 

00:40:40.360 --> 00:40:45.681
New York City has seven to
eight million people,

00:40:45.681 --> 00:40:52.704
cities in China that's a small
town almost, and India's not far

00:40:52.704 --> 00:40:53.949
behind.
 

00:40:53.949 --> 00:40:58.402
People in the United States
generally don't have much of an

00:40:58.402 --> 00:41:01.550
idea of what poverty really
looks like.

00:41:01.550 --> 00:41:05.407
One of the best descriptions of
this comes from Bill Ryerson who

00:41:05.407 --> 00:41:07.920
is going to be a guest lecturer
later,

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:11.420
and he describes flying into
Bombay,

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:14.045
and this is again a few years
back but in this period of

00:41:14.045 --> 00:41:16.719
extreme population explosion
that we're talking about.

00:41:16.719 --> 00:41:19.802
He goes to the airport,
and the airport is way outside

00:41:19.802 --> 00:41:22.070
the city as all airports have to
be,

00:41:22.070 --> 00:41:26.197
and by the international flight
schedules they come in early in

00:41:26.197 --> 00:41:27.130
the morning.
 

00:41:27.130 --> 00:41:29.179
He starts driving in and almost
immediately,

00:41:29.179 --> 00:41:33.097
at the airport,
he starts seeing poor people

00:41:33.097 --> 00:41:36.494
begging,
on the street you see shanty's

00:41:36.494 --> 00:41:38.650
that people are living in.
 

00:41:38.650 --> 00:41:42.693
When he comes into the denser
places people start begging and

00:41:42.693 --> 00:41:46.199
you see very commonly a mother
holding an infant,

00:41:46.199 --> 00:41:48.860
and you can look the infant is
clearly nearly dead,

00:41:48.860 --> 00:41:51.760
and the mother's 'please give
me something,

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:54.626
anything so that I can keep
this child alive until

00:41:54.626 --> 00:41:57.320
tomorrow,' and there's one after
the other,

00:41:57.320 --> 00:41:58.989
after the other and it gets
denser.

00:41:58.989 --> 00:42:01.639
And then the sun comes up and
it gets warm,

00:42:01.639 --> 00:42:06.108
India's generally a rather warm
country and there's all these

00:42:06.108 --> 00:42:09.543
jitney's and motorbikes,
and trucks, small trucks

00:42:09.543 --> 00:42:13.280
putting around and they don't
have good catalytic converters,

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:15.804
those are expensive because a
lot of them have platinum in

00:42:15.804 --> 00:42:18.159
them,
so they produce a lot of

00:42:18.159 --> 00:42:23.407
pollution and the air gets very
thick with this black smoke very

00:42:23.407 --> 00:42:25.806
early--
black soot whatever you want to

00:42:25.806 --> 00:42:29.039
call it in the early morning so
you're not breathing fresh air.

00:42:29.039 --> 00:42:32.329
And then of course they have no
toilets around,

00:42:32.329 --> 00:42:35.630
and you're going to read some
articles about what that means,

00:42:35.630 --> 00:42:38.750
and so very soon the stench of
human waste--

00:42:38.750 --> 00:42:41.190
you're on a main street going
into the main city,

00:42:41.190 --> 00:42:46.990
the stench of human waste comes
up at you and it smells terribly

00:42:46.990 --> 00:42:52.056
and more and more beggars and
it's just absolutely heart

00:42:52.056 --> 00:42:56.199
wrenching description of what's
going on.

00:42:56.199 --> 00:43:00.655
And then you think that here
are millions and millions of

00:43:00.655 --> 00:43:05.271
people that will never have a
real house, they live in some

00:43:05.271 --> 00:43:07.659
cardboard shack somewhere.
 

00:43:07.659 --> 00:43:11.240
They'll never have a real job,
they'll never probably go to

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:15.280
the bathroom in a toilet,
and they may never even breathe

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:19.931
a breath of fresh air,
so poverty is really a very,

00:43:19.931 --> 00:43:26.166
very serious kind of situation
and you can go to lots and lots

00:43:26.166 --> 00:43:32.710
of cities in the world and see
similar kinds of descriptions.

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:37.297
Now to do the numbers on this
poverty, so we compare it to the

00:43:37.297 --> 00:43:40.456
United States,
so General Motors before its

00:43:40.456 --> 00:43:41.809
recent demise.
 

00:43:41.809 --> 00:43:45.949
These numbers are three or four
years old,

00:43:45.949 --> 00:43:48.755
so they pay wages to the
workers, then they have health

00:43:48.755 --> 00:43:51.923
benefits which you've read about
as very high because they pay

00:43:51.923 --> 00:43:54.989
them for the rest of their life
and they pay pensions,

00:43:54.989 --> 00:43:58.039
so when you add all that up how
much lifetime they're going to

00:43:58.039 --> 00:44:00.840
pay for a worker and divide it
by the number of hours the

00:44:00.840 --> 00:44:05.478
worker works,
it comes out for General Motors

00:44:05.478 --> 00:44:12.230
was $80 an hour and that was
somewhere near a maximum for

00:44:12.230 --> 00:44:15.981
union wages,
not counting like airline

00:44:15.981 --> 00:44:19.190
pilots who get an awful lot more
than that.

00:44:19.190 --> 00:44:23.460
The upper middle class--that's
blue-collar workers at GM--

00:44:23.460 --> 00:44:28.063
the upper middle class people
mostly in this room are going to

00:44:28.063 --> 00:44:31.159
be earning an awful lot more
than that.

00:44:31.159 --> 00:44:35.663
On the other hand is the
poverty level which for a family

00:44:35.663 --> 00:44:41.391
of a mother,
father, and three children is

00:44:41.391 --> 00:44:47.364
defined as $24,000 a year,
that's the 2006 number,

00:44:47.364 --> 00:44:48.619
the official U.S.
 

00:44:48.619 --> 00:44:53.083
number which is $13.35 a day
per person, that's the poverty

00:44:53.083 --> 00:44:57.010
level as officially defined in
the United States.

00:44:57.010 --> 00:45:03.449
Wal-Mart, a worker,
a sales associate earns $6.10

00:45:03.449 --> 00:45:10.708
an hour or $12,000 a year--
$6.00 an hour--is $12,000 a

00:45:10.708 --> 00:45:17.945
year they are below poverty
level so the next step UP for a

00:45:17.945 --> 00:45:24.059
Wal-Mart worker is the official
poverty level.

00:45:24.059 --> 00:45:28.788
When you go to developing
countries you have to cut--to

00:45:28.788 --> 00:45:34.304
get any idea of a scale you have
to cut the Wal-Mart wages by at

00:45:34.304 --> 00:45:36.670
least a factor of four.
 

00:45:36.670 --> 00:45:43.389
Wal-Mart makes its pants in El
Salvador and the pants sell for,

00:45:43.389 --> 00:45:48.304
in this particular article,
on this $16.95 in their United

00:45:48.304 --> 00:45:51.715
States stores,
and how much do you think the

00:45:51.715 --> 00:45:55.340
women in El Salvador get to make
the pants, per pant?

00:45:55.340 --> 00:46:04.400
15 cents is the wage level that
they get for it.

00:46:04.400 --> 00:46:09.396
The UN reported that about half
of the world's workers,

00:46:09.396 --> 00:46:14.579
which is about 1.4 billion
people, earn less than $2.00 a

00:46:14.579 --> 00:46:15.320
day.
 

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:20.443
The average wage,
the median wage in the world is

00:46:20.443 --> 00:46:23.539
something like $2.00 a day.
 

00:46:23.539 --> 00:46:25.268
That's per wage earner,
not per family,

00:46:25.268 --> 00:46:28.882
not per person,
but per wage earner and that

00:46:28.882 --> 00:46:33.588
then has to be divided among
however many dependents that

00:46:33.588 --> 00:46:34.849
person has.
 

00:46:34.849 --> 00:46:36.394
I've told you that what the
U.S.

00:46:36.394 --> 00:46:38.489
sets as its official level for
poverty,

00:46:38.489 --> 00:46:42.387
every country in the world of
course gets to decide its own

00:46:42.387 --> 00:46:46.670
level of what poverty is,
and the official poverty level

00:46:46.670 --> 00:46:52.518
in the poorest ten to 20--
poorest 20 countries is $1.25.

00:46:52.518 --> 00:46:56.016
You're only poor if you earn
less than a $1.25 per capita,

00:46:56.016 --> 00:46:56.630
per day.
 

00:46:56.630 --> 00:47:02.422
In both China and India the
official poverty level is closer

00:47:02.422 --> 00:47:06.840
to $1.00 a day and this is at
2005 prices,

00:47:06.840 --> 00:47:11.139
again statistics are always a
couple of years behind things.

00:47:11.139 --> 00:47:15.224
In rich places like Latin
America and Eastern Europe $2.00

00:47:15.224 --> 00:47:19.382
a day is the more appropriate
poverty level and that is for

00:47:19.382 --> 00:47:24.309
all the developing countries,
$2.00 a day is the median,

00:47:24.309 --> 00:47:27.949
their own self-defined poverty
level.

00:47:27.949 --> 00:47:31.762
Within each country and each
region there's great inequality

00:47:31.762 --> 00:47:34.911
of course in income,
so about 1/3 of the people in

00:47:34.911 --> 00:47:37.889
Latin America are living on less
than $2.00 a day,

00:47:37.889 --> 00:47:41.768
2/3 of the people of Pakistan
live on less than 2/3--

00:47:41.768 --> 00:47:45.608
$2.00 a day,
but more than 58% of the

00:47:45.608 --> 00:47:51.260
population in Kenya lives on
less than $1.00 a day;

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:55.210
Brazil 25% of the people on
less than $1.00 a day;

00:47:55.210 --> 00:47:59.001
the whole of Sub-Saharan Africa
44% of the people on less than

00:47:59.001 --> 00:48:02.297
$1.00 a day and it's not only
these traditionally poor

00:48:02.297 --> 00:48:04.625
countries,
but in Romania,

00:48:04.625 --> 00:48:07.880
after the Soviet bloc fell
apart,

00:48:07.880 --> 00:48:10.780
40% of the people live on less
than $1.00 a day.

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:16.409
Indonesia had a government work
program so that people could get

00:48:16.409 --> 00:48:21.771
some kind of work and laborers
got $0.75 a day for five hours

00:48:21.771 --> 00:48:25.449
of work a day,
that's $0.15 an hour.

00:48:25.449 --> 00:48:29.213
I don't know how much time it
takes to sew Wal-Mart pants but

00:48:29.213 --> 00:48:32.443
maybe an hour,
probably less but--so $.15 an

00:48:32.443 --> 00:48:36.175
hour is a wage that for many
people in a place like

00:48:36.175 --> 00:48:38.849
Indonesia,
which has a lot of oil,

00:48:38.849 --> 00:48:41.969
it's not overall necessarily a
poor place,

00:48:41.969 --> 00:48:49.380
$0.15 an hour for an hour's
work;

00:48:49.380 --> 00:48:53.264
$0.75 a day and that's much
more than they can get

00:48:53.264 --> 00:48:58.018
working--getting agricultural
jobs around where they live.

00:48:58.018 --> 00:49:03.871
Here's a description from
Zambia, a nine-year-old boy,

00:49:03.871 --> 00:49:08.068
Alone Banda,
his job is to be beat rock

00:49:08.068 --> 00:49:10.940
fragments into powder.
 

00:49:10.940 --> 00:49:14.085
He doesn't have a hammer,
he found a large steel bolt

00:49:14.085 --> 00:49:16.813
from some construction site,
he found a bolt,

00:49:16.813 --> 00:49:19.750
he grips in his bare hand and
pounds the rock with it.

00:49:19.750 --> 00:49:23.559
He takes raw rock,
takes a bolt that he found and

00:49:23.559 --> 00:49:29.639
pounds with it and he can fill--
it takes him about a--in a week

00:49:29.639 --> 00:49:35.963
he can fill about half a bag
with this powder which is used

00:49:35.963 --> 00:49:42.505
for construction and he gets
about $1.50 for the half bag and

00:49:42.505 --> 00:49:48.719
it's used for making concrete in
Kenya for instance.

00:49:48.719 --> 00:49:50.210
Children start working at five
or six--

00:49:50.210 --> 00:49:53.635
we saw--we talked about Charles
Dickens who so much of his

00:49:53.635 --> 00:49:57.059
writing was about children going
to work at age seven,

00:49:57.059 --> 00:49:59.492
while seven is old,
they go to five and six and

00:49:59.492 --> 00:50:01.820
they work as prostitutes even at
that age;

00:50:01.820 --> 00:50:04.980
minors, construction workers,
pesticide sprayers,

00:50:04.980 --> 00:50:08.139
all the kinds of dangerous and
miserable jobs.

00:50:08.139 --> 00:50:12.269
In Sub-Saharan Africa there's
something like 48 million

00:50:12.269 --> 00:50:15.559
children 14 and younger who are
working,

00:50:15.559 --> 00:50:20.925
and four years later it says,
by 2004 it had increased by 1.3

00:50:20.925 --> 00:50:24.954
million,
so the number of children

00:50:24.954 --> 00:50:32.264
working at these poverty level
jobs is increasing because the

00:50:32.264 --> 00:50:37.989
whole population is increasing
and so forth.

00:50:37.989 --> 00:50:41.309
This is the poverty rates
around the world and just

00:50:41.309 --> 00:50:44.833
compare--
this confirms the numbers that

00:50:44.833 --> 00:50:50.048
I'm telling you that these are
the headcount in number of

00:50:50.048 --> 00:50:54.081
millions,
the percent below poverty line

00:50:54.081 --> 00:50:58.099
at $1.25 a day,
less than $2.00 a day,

00:50:58.099 --> 00:51:02.476
and if you take out China,
China is still one of the

00:51:02.476 --> 00:51:05.070
poorest places when you add in
all the peasants,

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:08.710
it doesn't get--it gets
some--actually China makes it

00:51:08.710 --> 00:51:11.340
worse,
when you add in China you have

00:51:11.340 --> 00:51:14.409
a higher percentage at these
poverty levels,

00:51:14.409 --> 00:51:17.480
same for whatever poverty level
you want to work.

00:51:17.480 --> 00:51:24.269
These are the appropriate
poverty levels for developing

00:51:24.269 --> 00:51:25.780
countries.
 

00:51:25.780 --> 00:51:30.219
Now, again you have the same
two ways of describing this--

00:51:30.219 --> 00:51:33.295
the absolute number of people
in this kind of poverty is

00:51:33.295 --> 00:51:35.621
growing up,
so as the whole population

00:51:35.621 --> 00:51:39.000
grows the number people in these
levels are growing up,

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:42.349
yet there has been economic
progress in the sense that,

00:51:42.349 --> 00:51:47.125
as a percentage of people,
the poverty numbers are going

00:51:47.125 --> 00:51:49.474
down,
so there's more people in

00:51:49.474 --> 00:51:52.914
poverty, but there's a lesser
percentage of the total

00:51:52.914 --> 00:51:54.570
population in poverty.
 

00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:56.891
Again, you can,
depending on your political

00:51:56.891 --> 00:51:59.208
orientation,
you can describe this as an

00:51:59.208 --> 00:52:02.737
increasingly bad situation where
more and more people are in this

00:52:02.737 --> 00:52:05.818
kind of poverty,
or a situation that is getting

00:52:05.818 --> 00:52:10.170
better because the percentage of
people in poverty is going down.

00:52:10.170 --> 00:52:17.601
Now the miracle--so you've all
heard of the economic miracle in

00:52:17.601 --> 00:52:20.360
East Asia especially.
 

00:52:20.360 --> 00:52:26.340
Anybody come fairly recently
from China?

00:52:26.340 --> 00:52:28.539
None of the students come from
China.

00:52:28.539 --> 00:52:31.190
Well the average income,
and again,

00:52:31.190 --> 00:52:34.000
income how you define--of
course the Chinese don't earn

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:37.226
dollars so when you express it
in dollars there's a translation

00:52:37.226 --> 00:52:40.090
and the best way of doing it is
what's called PPP,

00:52:40.090 --> 00:52:41.739
purchasing power parity.
 

00:52:41.739 --> 00:52:44.393
One way is to use the official
exchange rate,

00:52:44.393 --> 00:52:47.771
how many--they earn so many
Yuan and how many dollars can

00:52:47.771 --> 00:52:49.460
they buy with that Yuan?
 

00:52:49.460 --> 00:52:51.608
That exchange rate,
as you know especially in

00:52:51.608 --> 00:52:54.342
China, is manipulated by the
government and is not a real

00:52:54.342 --> 00:52:54.880
number.
 

00:52:54.880 --> 00:52:58.322
A number that makes the Chinese
income look more favorable and

00:52:58.322 --> 00:53:01.708
is closer to a real number is
what they call purchasing power

00:53:01.708 --> 00:53:02.329
parity.
 

00:53:02.329 --> 00:53:05.260
You say how much does a sack of
rice cost in China,

00:53:05.260 --> 00:53:07.579
how much does it cost in the
United States,

00:53:07.579 --> 00:53:11.849
and you try to use a basket of
commodities appropriate to what

00:53:11.849 --> 00:53:15.699
the people in that country
actually use and say how much

00:53:15.699 --> 00:53:19.619
would that cost in dollars so
you can have a parity.

00:53:19.619 --> 00:53:23.617
On that kind of a level,
a Chinese peasant on average

00:53:23.617 --> 00:53:25.309
earns a $1.00 a day.
 

00:53:25.309 --> 00:53:31.802
The person--a $1.00 is the
average income in the Chinese

00:53:31.802 --> 00:53:33.809
peasant family.
 

00:53:33.809 --> 00:53:36.659
The jobs in the modern sector,
which means one of these

00:53:36.659 --> 00:53:39.298
manufacturing jobs,
and they migrate to some city,

00:53:39.298 --> 00:53:42.259
they live in these dorm rooms
where they're just stacked like

00:53:42.259 --> 00:53:44.847
cord wood,
and they basically have no free

00:53:44.847 --> 00:53:47.786
time and they're--
it's a miserable life but they

00:53:47.786 --> 00:53:49.030
double their income.
 

00:53:49.030 --> 00:53:54.695
The economic miracle in Asia is
when people go from $1.00 a day

00:53:54.695 --> 00:53:57.907
to $2.00 a day,
and there's hundreds of

00:53:57.907 --> 00:54:01.280
millions of people,
you add up China and India,

00:54:01.280 --> 00:54:05.663
hundreds of millions of people
who are desperate to earn $2.00

00:54:05.663 --> 00:54:08.630
a day;
it's a doubling of their income.

00:54:08.630 --> 00:54:09.768
When you read these horrible
stories,

00:54:09.768 --> 00:54:13.130
horrible to our ears,
of how, especially women,

00:54:13.130 --> 00:54:15.679
moving into the big cities
Guangdong,

00:54:15.679 --> 00:54:18.677
Canton or any of the big
cities, how they're living and

00:54:18.677 --> 00:54:20.900
the conditions they're working
under,

00:54:20.900 --> 00:54:23.353
remember it represents a
doubling of their income and

00:54:23.353 --> 00:54:27.228
it's so much--
they can send most of that back

00:54:27.228 --> 00:54:33.367
to their home village and home
villages are all living on this

00:54:33.367 --> 00:54:35.179
kind of income.
 

00:54:35.179 --> 00:54:39.146
When we talk about poverty--we
will later talk about population

00:54:39.146 --> 00:54:43.112
in China - you must realize that
basically all of those workers

00:54:43.112 --> 00:54:46.501
who now have access to
moderately decent education can

00:54:46.501 --> 00:54:47.909
compete with us.
 

00:54:47.909 --> 00:54:51.179
There's very few jobs that we
can do and they can't do,

00:54:51.179 --> 00:54:54.675
and so we at up to $80 an hour
for a blue collar worker are

00:54:54.675 --> 00:54:58.170
basically in competition with
someone who's very happy--

00:54:58.170 --> 00:55:00.869
and they grumble,
people working for GM grumble,

00:55:00.869 --> 00:55:04.083
and in some of their conditions
the grumbling could be quite

00:55:04.083 --> 00:55:07.143
fair--
but they're in competition with

00:55:07.143 --> 00:55:11.365
people earning $2.00,
that wish they would earn $2.00

00:55:11.365 --> 00:55:11.880
a day.
 

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:18.320
In places--this is not only our
competition but jewelry making,

00:55:18.320 --> 00:55:22.449
very labor intensive--of course
countries with low wage rates

00:55:22.449 --> 00:55:26.510
attract very labor intensive
jobs and hand making of jewelry

00:55:26.510 --> 00:55:28.849
is a very labor intensive job.
 

00:55:28.849 --> 00:55:32.369
Sure enough,
Bangkok was one of the centers

00:55:32.369 --> 00:55:35.385
of jewelry making,
and because it was the center

00:55:35.385 --> 00:55:37.159
and it requires a fair amount of
skill,

00:55:37.159 --> 00:55:41.586
the wages actually rose in
Bangkok for these jewelry makers

00:55:41.586 --> 00:55:46.550
and they got up to $8.00 a day
for a jewelry worker in Bangkok.

00:55:46.550 --> 00:55:48.260
Guess what happened?
 

00:55:48.260 --> 00:55:51.429
All the factories moved to
China, they're back down to

00:55:51.429 --> 00:55:54.480
$2.00 a day, a saving of 75% on
your labor costs;

00:55:54.480 --> 00:55:55.869
of course they're going to do
it.

00:55:55.869 --> 00:55:59.500
Not only in China,
but Mexico, all the

00:55:59.500 --> 00:56:03.096
maquiladoras,
the border between Texas and

00:56:03.096 --> 00:56:07.295
California and Mexico has a lot
of factories and because of

00:56:07.295 --> 00:56:11.349
various trade laws they can
assemble things and just ship

00:56:11.349 --> 00:56:16.199
them across the border with low
trade tariffs and everything,

00:56:16.199 --> 00:56:20.739
and they have been nearly wiped
out with jobs moving to China.

00:56:20.739 --> 00:56:22.585
Now of course,
for a while anyway,

00:56:22.585 --> 00:56:25.608
conditions were getting a
little bit better in China so

00:56:25.608 --> 00:56:26.840
the jobs moved to?
 

00:56:26.840 --> 00:56:28.989
Anyone reading the newspapers?
 

00:56:28.989 --> 00:56:32.559
Who's now competing with China?
 

00:56:32.559 --> 00:56:35.525
India, at a high level,
but Vietnam,

00:56:35.525 --> 00:56:40.608
Cambodia, places that are even
poorer than China are now even

00:56:40.608 --> 00:56:43.320
taking jobs away from China.
 

00:56:43.320 --> 00:56:49.565
In Romania, which is one of the
poorest countries in Europe,

00:56:49.565 --> 00:56:55.813
the wages average about $83.00
a week, so $10.00 or $12.00 a

00:56:55.813 --> 00:56:56.659
day.
 

00:56:56.659 --> 00:57:00.809
When they got into the European
Union what did the Romanian

00:57:00.809 --> 00:57:01.739
workers do?
 

00:57:01.739 --> 00:57:05.864
They moved out to France,
Germany, England to get the

00:57:05.864 --> 00:57:10.704
higher wages that are available
there which left a lot of jobs

00:57:10.704 --> 00:57:15.387
unfilled in Romania where they
get $12.00 a day as I've just

00:57:15.387 --> 00:57:16.260
said.
 

00:57:16.260 --> 00:57:18.909
What did the Romanians do?
 

00:57:18.909 --> 00:57:21.744
Imported Chinese,
who worked for less and filled

00:57:21.744 --> 00:57:24.463
the jobs,
there's an unlimited number of

00:57:24.463 --> 00:57:28.250
peasants in China that would
love to work in Romania under

00:57:28.250 --> 00:57:31.581
almost any kind of conditions,
and they leave their husbands,

00:57:31.581 --> 00:57:34.311
their children,
everybody is left home usually

00:57:34.311 --> 00:57:38.483
under the care of grandparents
who are too old themselves to

00:57:38.483 --> 00:57:39.050
work.
 

00:57:39.050 --> 00:57:44.668
Keep that in mind,
abject poverty is a $1.00 a

00:57:44.668 --> 00:57:50.039
day, the economic miracle is
$2.00 a day.

00:57:50.039 --> 00:57:56.460
Okay, what does living look
like in these places?

00:57:56.460 --> 00:57:59.846
We've been talking about
Bombay, and Shanghai,

00:57:59.846 --> 00:58:03.610
these are big places that
everybody knows about.

00:58:03.610 --> 00:58:06.476
You'll never guess where this
is and you've probably never

00:58:06.476 --> 00:58:07.179
heard of it.
 

00:58:07.179 --> 00:58:09.139
This is the capital of
Mauritania.

00:58:09.139 --> 00:58:11.800
How many know where Mauritania
is?

00:58:11.800 --> 00:58:14.130
Good, it's on the Atlantic
coast of Africa.

00:58:14.130 --> 00:58:17.668
I should remember to always
make a slide--geography map

00:58:17.668 --> 00:58:19.110
slides but I didn't.
 

00:58:19.110 --> 00:58:22.666
It's on the Atlantic coast it
is--the capital is a place

00:58:22.666 --> 00:58:23.960
called Nouakchott.
 

00:58:23.960 --> 00:58:28.007
Nouakchott is over there
somewhere and this is the

00:58:28.007 --> 00:58:32.550
suburbs of Nouakchott and what
it is is desert it's--

00:58:32.550 --> 00:58:36.268
all of Mauritania is basically
desert,

00:58:36.268 --> 00:58:38.762
until it rolls into the ocean
in which case it becomes an

00:58:38.762 --> 00:58:39.119
ocean.
 

00:58:39.119 --> 00:58:44.891
In the desert all these people
live in shanties of any kind of

00:58:44.891 --> 00:58:48.960
construction material that they
can find.

00:58:48.960 --> 00:58:52.152
The national government,
the city government does not

00:58:52.152 --> 00:58:55.530
have the resources to deal with
these people at all,

00:58:55.530 --> 00:58:59.349
so they get no sanitation,
they get no policing,

00:58:59.349 --> 00:59:02.972
they get no water,
there's just--these are called

00:59:02.972 --> 00:59:07.730
unplanned communities and they
sort of basically don't exist.

00:59:07.730 --> 00:59:09.639
What are they to the government?
 

00:59:09.639 --> 00:59:12.737
They're a source of problems
because very poor people,

00:59:12.737 --> 00:59:15.659
who have nothing to lose,
revolt every so often.

00:59:15.659 --> 00:59:18.190
They say you've got something,
we don't have it,

00:59:18.190 --> 00:59:21.115
we want it, why is the
government not doing anything

00:59:21.115 --> 00:59:23.746
for us,
so this is a source of social

00:59:23.746 --> 00:59:26.347
discontent,
and the shanty towns are around

00:59:26.347 --> 00:59:29.271
every big city in the world are
great sources of social

00:59:29.271 --> 00:59:30.030
discontent.
 

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:32.974
What you see here is a road,
and I've just said they

00:59:32.974 --> 00:59:34.650
basically don't have roads.
 

00:59:34.650 --> 00:59:37.777
What happens is that the
military in each of these

00:59:37.777 --> 00:59:41.800
countries wants to be sure to be
able to control the people,

00:59:41.800 --> 00:59:44.230
so every so often they send in
a bulldozer,

00:59:44.230 --> 00:59:48.440
you can sort of see another
road here off to the right.

00:59:48.440 --> 00:59:52.422
Let me get a better one of
these--they just come in one

00:59:52.422 --> 00:59:56.699
morning and the people are
asleep in their shanty's because

00:59:56.699 --> 00:59:58.840
they don't have any jobs.
 

00:59:58.840 --> 01:00:02.210
And very early in the morning
they just hear this rumble and

01:00:02.210 --> 01:00:05.639
they walk outside to find out
what it is and the bulldozer is

01:00:05.639 --> 01:00:08.952
two minutes away from their
house and they just go down and

01:00:08.952 --> 01:00:11.409
knock out anything that's in the
way.

01:00:11.409 --> 01:00:14.931
If you happen to be in the path
that the military bulldoze

01:00:14.931 --> 01:00:17.489
knocks down,
well sorry, sorry,

01:00:17.489 --> 01:00:21.114
that's gone,
and then the soldiers can go

01:00:21.114 --> 01:00:23.380
into these situations.
 

01:00:23.380 --> 01:00:28.489
The point being that these
enormous dense populations,

01:00:28.489 --> 01:00:31.809
which we associate with
Calcutta or Bombay,

01:00:31.809 --> 01:00:35.690
or Shanghai,
Canton, are in fact almost

01:00:35.690 --> 01:00:40.389
everywhere in the world now
including this--

01:00:40.389 --> 01:00:45.179
this is where Nouakchott meets
the Atlantic Ocean.

01:00:45.179 --> 01:00:49.170
Here's the Atlantic Ocean
there, and what do they live on?

01:00:49.170 --> 01:00:53.237
Well they live on fishing and
each of these little things

01:00:53.237 --> 01:00:56.070
here, if you can see,
is a fishing boat,

01:00:56.070 --> 01:00:59.340
a little boat that they row out
and fish.

01:00:59.340 --> 01:01:02.369
Look at how many boats there
are, all trying to get an

01:01:02.369 --> 01:01:05.969
occasional fish and that's not a
terribly rich fishing ground of

01:01:05.969 --> 01:01:06.768
the world.
 

01:01:06.768 --> 01:01:10.085
It's very close to the equator
and there's no big upwelling of

01:01:10.085 --> 01:01:13.130
nutrients, there's not a great
big fishing down there.

01:01:13.130 --> 01:01:17.942
This is how the people have
been competing with each other

01:01:17.942 --> 01:01:21.150
for the few fish that are out
there.

01:01:21.150 --> 01:01:24.179
Now--so that's the desert and
here is the jungle.

01:01:24.179 --> 01:01:29.615
This is Brazil in a place that
you may have heard of Serra

01:01:29.615 --> 01:01:32.094
Pelada,
peeled mountain or naked

01:01:32.094 --> 01:01:35.974
mountain, anybody who has heard
of it or seen pictures of this

01:01:35.974 --> 01:01:36.610
before?
 

01:01:36.610 --> 01:01:39.400
One--a couple of people,
it's very well known,

01:01:39.400 --> 01:01:42.717
so if you travel in Brazil all
the big cities again have shanty

01:01:42.717 --> 01:01:45.820
towns where people are desperate
for some kind of a job.

01:01:45.820 --> 01:01:49.559
Every so often a truck rolls
through and says,

01:01:49.559 --> 01:01:51.768
I have some jobs,
and people just pile in,

01:01:51.768 --> 01:01:54.280
and I've watched it,
and they don't ask how much,

01:01:54.280 --> 01:01:56.809
where am I going,
what's the kind of work;

01:01:56.809 --> 01:02:00.005
a job is like a magic word,
it's like manna from heaven,

01:02:00.005 --> 01:02:01.460
they jump in the truck.
 

01:02:01.460 --> 01:02:05.260
Well one of the places you're
taken to is this place,

01:02:05.260 --> 01:02:07.000
and this place is way in the
middle of the jungle,

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:11.440
like 1,000 miles from Rio or
Sao Paolo and what it is,

01:02:11.440 --> 01:02:14.449
it's a mountain that they found
gold in.

01:02:14.449 --> 01:02:18.166
Normally if you've seen like
mining in the western United

01:02:18.166 --> 01:02:22.014
States they have these steam
shovels which have a bucket as

01:02:22.014 --> 01:02:27.365
big as this whole room probably,
and each drag of the bucket

01:02:27.365 --> 01:02:33.059
pulls up hundreds of tons,
I don't know the actual numbers.

01:02:33.059 --> 01:02:38.331
In Serra Pelada,
human labor is cheaper than to

01:02:38.331 --> 01:02:40.739
buy a steam shovel.
 

01:02:40.739 --> 01:02:44.400
What each of these little dots
are is a person.

01:02:44.400 --> 01:02:45.063
What it is?
 

01:02:45.063 --> 01:02:48.260
This is a pit and they're
digging in the mud there,

01:02:48.260 --> 01:02:51.746
they carry the mud up--the
sluicing is up here on the top

01:02:51.746 --> 01:02:54.577
where they have--
sluicing is--gold is heavier

01:02:54.577 --> 01:02:57.324
than soil so they take,
basically mud,

01:02:57.324 --> 01:03:01.050
dump it into someplace,
water runs over it,

01:03:01.050 --> 01:03:04.507
washes away the mud,
and anything that sticks down

01:03:04.507 --> 01:03:07.820
falls heavy in little flakes or
tiny nuggets of gold;

01:03:07.820 --> 01:03:11.230
that's the primitive way of
doing gold mining.

01:03:11.230 --> 01:03:14.394
Just flow water over mud and
there's very,

01:03:14.394 --> 01:03:18.409
very low concentration you get
a gold flake there.

01:03:18.409 --> 01:03:21.679
What do these people--how do
they work?

01:03:21.679 --> 01:03:26.195
This is--they go down,
then climb--these are wooden

01:03:26.195 --> 01:03:29.163
ladders,
and another part they climb

01:03:29.163 --> 01:03:33.550
down the ladders and they have
burlap sacks on their back,

01:03:33.550 --> 01:03:36.139
the cheapest kind of sack,
and they go down and with very

01:03:36.139 --> 01:03:38.219
primitive implements or maybe
their hands,

01:03:38.219 --> 01:03:41.268
they take the earth from the
bottom of the pit,

01:03:41.268 --> 01:03:44.485
they put it in these packs,
they put the pack on their back

01:03:44.485 --> 01:03:47.534
and they climb up the stairs and
dump it into the sluice

01:03:47.534 --> 01:03:49.530
apparatus and then go back down.
 

01:03:49.530 --> 01:03:51.360
That's their whole life.
 

01:03:51.360 --> 01:03:53.583
There are miserable wages,
they can't leave because

01:03:53.583 --> 01:03:56.029
they're in the middle of the
jungle, they have no way of

01:03:56.029 --> 01:03:58.030
getting back to any kind of
civilization.

01:03:58.030 --> 01:04:00.518
The companies do indeed provide
prostitutes for them.

01:04:00.518 --> 01:04:03.215
This whole village is full of
prostitutes which are the women

01:04:03.215 --> 01:04:04.789
that come out the same
situation.

01:04:04.789 --> 01:04:08.418
Send a truck around and say
they have jobs for women,

01:04:08.418 --> 01:04:11.840
they jump on with little or no
questions asked.

01:04:11.840 --> 01:04:15.018
How is the whole thing kept
under control?

01:04:15.018 --> 01:04:19.280
By soldiers with guns or
paramilitaries with guns,

01:04:19.280 --> 01:04:25.152
and here is moderately typical,
one of the workers has not even

01:04:25.152 --> 01:04:29.106
the clothes on his back,
and there's huge numbers of

01:04:29.106 --> 01:04:30.920
them and they are kept in
control.

01:04:30.920 --> 01:04:34.168
In this particular instance the
things were looking like they

01:04:34.168 --> 01:04:36.010
were going to go out of control.
 

01:04:36.010 --> 01:04:45.211
Again, this is all around the
world you'll find situations

01:04:45.211 --> 01:04:47.150
like this.
 

01:04:55.780 --> 01:04:59.230
Sometimes I talk
about--everywhere in the world.

01:04:59.230 --> 01:04:59.947
If you go up to Mt.
 

01:04:59.947 --> 01:05:01.909
Everest--we've got--what are
the ends of the earth?

01:05:01.909 --> 01:05:04.251
There's the deserts,
there's the jungles,

01:05:04.251 --> 01:05:05.128
and there's Mt.
 

01:05:05.128 --> 01:05:08.172
Everest and I just copied down
some statistics on Mt.

01:05:08.172 --> 01:05:11.449
Everest, how much population
there is in the world.

01:05:11.449 --> 01:05:16.637
There's--up high,
and I used to mountain climb a

01:05:16.637 --> 01:05:18.847
lot,
a single footstep can require

01:05:18.847 --> 01:05:21.597
eight breaths,
you take a step you pant eight

01:05:21.597 --> 01:05:23.858
times,
and people like me it would be

01:05:23.858 --> 01:05:25.539
a lot more than eight times.
 

01:05:25.539 --> 01:05:28.436
On one particular day,
and standard in the couple of

01:05:28.436 --> 01:05:31.846
months that you can climb it,
there's 500 climbers waiting to

01:05:31.846 --> 01:05:33.039
climb up Everest.
 

01:05:33.039 --> 01:05:37.440
The place is just littered with
dead bodies, it's littered with

01:05:37.440 --> 01:05:39.215
oxygen bottles,
I mean Mt.

01:05:39.215 --> 01:05:43.190
Everest is kind of a congestion
zone, it looks like Grand

01:05:43.190 --> 01:05:47.592
Central Station that have been
sort of cleared out of people on

01:05:47.592 --> 01:05:48.869
many days.
 

01:05:48.869 --> 01:05:52.567
There's 120 dead bodies
littering the top of Mt.

01:05:52.567 --> 01:05:57.050
Everest, so population has
gotten so extreme that it's not

01:05:57.050 --> 01:06:00.983
only the big cities,
it's basically everywhere that

01:06:00.983 --> 01:06:03.030
you look people are.
 

01:06:03.030 --> 01:06:08.719
Let's just conclude today with
a little bit of future guessing.

01:06:08.719 --> 01:06:13.561
We know that fertility--so now
we have most of the world at a

01:06:13.561 --> 01:06:18.159
very high fertility rate,
population going gangbusters.

01:06:18.159 --> 01:06:22.250
Now can we dream up a scenario
where this gets better?

01:06:22.250 --> 01:06:24.590
It may get better,
it may not get better,

01:06:24.590 --> 01:06:27.306
things may get worse until
there's some incredible crisis

01:06:27.306 --> 01:06:29.150
or things may stay as they are
now,

01:06:29.150 --> 01:06:32.809
or things may coast to a soft
landing,

01:06:32.809 --> 01:06:33.289
we don't know.
 

01:06:33.289 --> 01:06:40.030
Let's draw ourselves a scenario
for the soft landing situation.

01:06:40.030 --> 01:06:42.768
One of the things that we know
is that there's very,

01:06:42.768 --> 01:06:45.257
very poor people,
these $1.00 a day people don't

01:06:45.257 --> 01:06:48.380
limit their births and the exact
reason for it we'll discuss

01:06:48.380 --> 01:06:48.909
later.
 

01:06:48.909 --> 01:06:50.369
A lot of it has to do with
education,

01:06:50.369 --> 01:06:52.786
that they don't--a lot of
things about how their bodies

01:06:52.786 --> 01:06:55.737
work they don't understand,
so they're afraid of modern

01:06:55.737 --> 01:06:59.628
contraception,
a lot of issues which we will

01:06:59.628 --> 01:07:00.539
discuss.
 

01:07:00.539 --> 01:07:04.398
We observe around the world
that some increase in standard

01:07:04.398 --> 01:07:06.768
of living has to take place
for--

01:07:06.768 --> 01:07:12.510
before people start being
willing and want to limit their

01:07:12.510 --> 01:07:13.739
fertility.
 

01:07:13.739 --> 01:07:17.255
Let's take the minimum
situation, let's say someone

01:07:17.255 --> 01:07:20.699
gets one of these $2.00 a day
jobs and that's--

01:07:20.699 --> 01:07:24.469
then they start thinking
differently about themselves in

01:07:24.469 --> 01:07:26.324
the world,
they may be in the city where

01:07:26.324 --> 01:07:28.782
they get some education,
some awareness of what's going

01:07:28.782 --> 01:07:31.061
on in the world,
they want to limit their

01:07:31.061 --> 01:07:34.418
population so let's say that we
go from $1.00 a day to $2.00 a

01:07:34.418 --> 01:07:36.505
day,
that's incredibly optimistic

01:07:36.505 --> 01:07:40.090
that $2.00 a day is sufficient
but you'll see what-- where I'm

01:07:40.090 --> 01:07:40.619
going.
 

01:07:40.619 --> 01:07:42.829
That's a doubling of income of
the poor people.

01:07:42.829 --> 01:07:45.530
Again, something like a third
of the people on earth are in

01:07:45.530 --> 01:07:49.681
this $1.00 to $2.00 a day range,
so you double their income and

01:07:49.681 --> 01:07:54.809
all of sudden miracles happen
and population stops growing,

01:07:54.809 --> 01:07:57.739
not real, way overly optimistic.
 

01:07:57.739 --> 01:08:01.639
Another thing that we know is
that when incomes around the

01:08:01.639 --> 01:08:05.811
world rise the poor people have
the smallest rise and the rich

01:08:05.811 --> 01:08:08.070
people have the biggest rise.
 

01:08:08.070 --> 01:08:10.965
If the small people are
doubling their income,

01:08:10.965 --> 01:08:13.989
what is the average of the
whole world doing?

01:08:13.989 --> 01:08:15.889
It's going to be much then
doubling.

01:08:15.889 --> 01:08:18.743
Again, you can pick--I'm sure
economists have these numbers,

01:08:18.743 --> 01:08:21.260
I don't have them,
you can pick whatever you want.

01:08:21.260 --> 01:08:24.582
If in order to raise most of
the world from $1.00 a day to

01:08:24.582 --> 01:08:28.136
$2.00 a day you need to double
their income and does the whole

01:08:28.136 --> 01:08:31.109
world rise by more than 2 times
maybe 3 times,

01:08:31.109 --> 01:08:33.930
but we can pick any number that
we want.

01:08:33.930 --> 01:08:37.009
I've told you two facts,
that the population of the

01:08:37.009 --> 01:08:40.457
world is for sure going to
increase by something like 50%

01:08:40.457 --> 01:08:42.859
before, if, and when it
stabilizes.

01:08:42.859 --> 01:08:47.689
We can sort of see ballpark a
50% increase coming.

01:08:47.689 --> 01:08:51.988
Now, but this average standard
of living has to at least

01:08:51.988 --> 01:08:54.132
double,
and probably triple or

01:08:54.132 --> 01:08:57.788
quadruple, or again pick almost
whatever number you want,

01:08:57.788 --> 01:09:02.149
so at the minimum of doubling
the world's per capita income,

01:09:02.149 --> 01:09:06.908
50% more people are doubling
the income means a three--

01:09:06.908 --> 01:09:10.993
that the gross economy,
well it has to triple because

01:09:10.993 --> 01:09:13.819
you have 1.5 time as many
people,

01:09:13.819 --> 01:09:17.648
each earning twice as much,
that's a tripling of the world

01:09:17.648 --> 01:09:18.319
economy.
 

01:09:18.319 --> 01:09:22.310
If you want to say that the
world--that to double the income

01:09:22.310 --> 01:09:26.029
of poor people you have to
triple the world economy,

01:09:26.029 --> 01:09:29.500
then that's three times more or
four and half times as much.

01:09:29.500 --> 01:09:32.953
Basically we're looking at a
optimistic scenario for the

01:09:32.953 --> 01:09:36.594
future where we come to a soft
landing and then in order to

01:09:36.594 --> 01:09:40.487
come to a soft landing we have
to have the economy of the world

01:09:40.487 --> 01:09:43.887
increase by a factor of three,
by a factor of four,

01:09:43.887 --> 01:09:47.970
four and a half,
five, six, somewhere in that

01:09:47.970 --> 01:09:49.970
range of numbers.
 

01:09:49.970 --> 01:09:53.988
Now technology--the improvement
of technology allows us to grow

01:09:53.988 --> 01:09:56.212
our income with--
a somewhat less than

01:09:56.212 --> 01:09:58.100
proportionate increase in
resources,

01:09:58.100 --> 01:10:01.747
and again, you can make a wild
guess about how much technology

01:10:01.747 --> 01:10:05.217
will improve in the future so
that we can double our income

01:10:05.217 --> 01:10:09.046
without quite doubling the drain
on world's sources or the amount

01:10:09.046 --> 01:10:12.708
of pollution we put it into,
or the amount of carbon dioxide

01:10:12.708 --> 01:10:13.520
we put into it.
 

01:10:13.520 --> 01:10:17.372
We're looking at this enormous
increase in order to come to a

01:10:17.372 --> 01:10:20.405
soft landing,
we're looking at this at least

01:10:20.405 --> 01:10:24.572
a tripling of the world economy,
and something like a tripling

01:10:24.572 --> 01:10:28.648
of the pollution in the world,
the carbon dioxide in the

01:10:28.648 --> 01:10:31.988
world, the use of resources in
the world.

01:10:31.988 --> 01:10:36.480
Most people believe that we're
at the limit of what the earth

01:10:36.480 --> 01:10:39.550
can cope with in terms of the
economy,

01:10:39.550 --> 01:10:41.609
which is basically how much
we're taking out of the earth.

01:10:41.609 --> 01:10:45.042
We're at the limit right now
but with population we're not

01:10:45.042 --> 01:10:48.051
going to have a soft landing
unless we triple that,

01:10:48.051 --> 01:10:50.038
at least minimum triple that.
 

01:10:50.038 --> 01:10:55.940
That's the significance of this
population issue that can the

01:10:55.940 --> 01:11:02.038
earth cope with the tripling of
the economic activity on it?

01:11:02.038 --> 01:11:04.815
I left my crystal ball home so
you're going to--you are

01:11:04.815 --> 01:11:07.850
definitely going to find out the
answer to that question.

01:11:07.850 --> 01:11:10.970
Okay, next time we will
continue.

